column1: How many fatalities will result from fighting between the armed forces of Azerbaijan and either the Nagorno-Karabakh Defense Army or the armed forces of Armenia between 20 June 2017 and 1 July 2018?
column6: ['Security and Conflict']
column11: All fatalities resulting from the fighting, including civilians and third party actors will count. The once “frozen” conflict between Azerbaijan and Armenian separatists in Nagorno-Karabakh has shown signs of escalation (Reuters, Aljazeera, Council on Foreign Relations). The answer options represent different orders of magnitude of conflict escalation. Fatality estimates often vary across sources and are typically reported in ranges. If the fatality estimates from open source media coverage produce a range that crosses two of the answer bins, GJ will generally use the higher end of the range to determine the resolution of the question, but will also consider the number of sources that put the high end of the range within each bin as well as how much of the total range falls within each bin. Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

I think there is a 95% chance this will end in between 10 and 99 fatalities and a 5% this will end in 100-999. I think this because the conflict is only continuing to escalate, especially in terms of violence, and also territorial disputes are one the most major causes of war.
Constant daily shelling from Armenia, both sides. Probably under under orders not to fire, or respond to avoid de-escalation. Two Armenian soldiers this year. Are Azerbaijanis getting drawn in?

The average number of fatalities per year in conflicts between the the armed forces of Azerbaijan and either the Nagorno-Karabakh Defense Army or the armed forces of Armenia has been of the order of 50 of the past 10 years, with the 200+ casualties of the 2016 confrontation contributing a lot to that number.
An Armenian soldier killed:

With the exception of 2016, which saw an abnormally high number of casualties in Nagorno-Karabakh (around 220 combat casualties), 2014 and 2015 saw 60 and 90 combat casualties, respectively. Estimates for the entirety of 2017 show about 50 combat deaths, which included 2 deadly attacks in February (not included in the time period for the question). Since June 2017, fighting in the region has been mostly limited to occasional skirmishes and disputes. Although data on all fatalities (not just combat) is not readily available, I would expect that lower levels of fighting between either Armenia or Nagorno-Karabakh and Azerbaijan would result in a reduced number of civilian and third-party casualties as well. The number of fatalities for this time period is already in the 10-99 range and there is a low chance fatalities will exceed 99 in the given time period due to this reduced fighting. For this reason, I think there is an 88% chance that between 20 June 2017 and 1 July 2018 there will be 10-99 fatalities and only a 12% chance for 100-999 fatalities. I think there is a 0% chance for 1,000 or more fatalities because that would require a scale of fighting that would severely interrupt oil and gas exports in the region, which goes against the broader interests Azerbaijan. https://www.cfr.org/interactives/global-conflict-tracker?marker=23#!/conflict/nagorno-karabakh-conflict https://eurasianet.org/s/karabakh-more-relative-calm-ahead-in-2018

This is part of bigger picture. In Nagorno-Karabakh conflict, Armenia (Nagorno-Karabakh Defense Army) is backed by Russia and Azerbaijan is backed by Turkey. Nothing serious will happen here without Putin's or Erdogan's permission. It was clearly seen in 2015/2016 when Turkey downed Russian fighter jet over Syria conflict in Nagorno Karabakh escalated and casualties skyrocketed. After 2016 failed coup in Turkey relations between Putin and Erdogan improved significantly. Probably thanks to the fact that Putin warned Erdogan. Why he did it despite recently dawned plane? Putin needed ally in Syria rather then foe as well as he took opportunity to create disagreement among strong NATO members Turkey and USA. Now Erdogans blames USA for supporting failed coup.

Another Azeri soldier has been killed (https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/karabakh/2782181.html). This puts the fatalities at 8-11, depending which news source is reporting. If this trend of ceasefire violations continues, it's likely this will become an over-under on the 100 mark.

Slightly increasing the likelihood of breaking 100 based on recent news reporting (22 June: http://asbarez.com/164497/4-azerbaijani-soldier-killed-after-artsakh-forces-rebuff-attack/, 5 July: https://www.reuters.com/article/us-armenia-azerbaijan-conflict-idUSKBN19Q1VG, 10 July: https://news.am/eng/news/399672.html), which puts the total dead at 7 since June 20. 3 Armenian soldiers were also injured during an Azerbaijani attack on July 7th, but reporting indicates they are still alive and recovering. Still 7 dead and at least 3 wounded in the past month doesn't indicate things will improve.

The fall of the buckets makes this particularly tricky – not that every other element of the Nagorno-Karabakh conflict isn’t already complex.

Azerbaijan is the state that holds the most power in the conflict over the Nagorno-Karabakh region. Thus far, the Armenian contingent within the Azerbaijani borders have acted as the aggressor and the fatality count is low. The attacks were mortars and, as in most wars, civilians were the majority of the fatalities. The situation could be compared to the start of a bad year in Israel. Most sources say the fatality count is now 2.

High likelihood of occasional mortar fire, mines, and sniper fire causing small numbers (10-99) of casualties, but none of the parties involved -- or their proxies -- want to escalate tensions over N-K that could spark a serious regional armed conflict.
new tactic from Armenia to conflagrate?

All of the outside forces (Russia, Turkey, Iran, USA, Georgia) would not benefit from a large conflict with thousands killed and they would probably work hard to keep that from happening so 1,000 or more may be unlikely. Smaller incidents are very likely with so many forces so close to each other and more than 100 fatalities have occurred in recent years.
Unfortunately, it appears the casualty count for the period begins (http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-40504373).

Peace attempts are in progress, but yielding little results (https://www.azernews.az/karabakh/115622.html). If this conflict does erupt, casualties will likely exceed 100, and if the fighting is prolonged, over 1,00 becomes much more likely. In the 1988-1994 Nagorno-Karabahk War, combined casualties exceeded 27,000 on the lower estimate (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nagorno-Karabakh_War).
